1. Project Definition & Overview ¶

Intro¶

Sparkify is a music streaming service (similar to Apple Music and Spotify), and can be used for free, or if the customer wants there are also paid plans which eliminate advertising.

The data provided is the log of the users interactions with the service/application. Every event/interaction is recorded with the following information:

root |-- artist: string (nullable = true) |-- auth: string (nullable = true) |-- firstName: string (nullable = true) |-- gender: string (nullable = true) |-- itemInSession: long (nullable = true) |-- lastName: string (nullable = true) |-- length: double (nullable = true) |-- level: string (nullable = true) |-- location: string (nullable = true) |-- method: string (nullable = true) |-- page: string (nullable = true) |-- registration: long (nullable = true) |-- sessionId: long (nullable = true) |-- song: string (nullable = true) |-- status: long (nullable = true) |-- ts: long (nullable = true) |-- userAgent: string (nullable = true) |-- userId: string (nullable = true)

This project has 4 main stages:

  1. Loading and cleaning data
    1. Load dataset
    2. Cleaning missing or invalid data
  2. Exploratory Data Analysis
    1. Define Churn & Downgrades from the original features
    2. Explore data (analysing interactions from both type of users: those who churned and those who didn't)
  3. Feature Engineering
    1. Build meaningfull features from the original dataset for each user, that represent the overall experience in Sparkify
    2. Save final dataset with engineered features
  4. Model training and Prediction
    1. Split data into training and testing data sets
    2. Train several classification models & Hyperparameter tunning with Grid Search
    3. Select best machine learning model based on f1score

In this project I'll be using Spark (PySpark) for all the data manipulation, loading, cleaning, feature engineering and Machine Learning. This workspace contains a tiny subset (128MB) of the full dataset available (12GB). This workspace is used to build the project, or to explore a smaller subset with Spark. The code can then be deployed on the cloud.

Problem Definition¶

The aim of this project is to predict customer churn based on its usage history/log. For that purpose it will be needed to generate new meaningfull features that characterize user experience in Sparkify, so that we can use a machine learning model to predict which customers are likely to churn.

For the prediction part I'll be using use F1 score to select the best machine learning model since the churned users are a fairly small subset (highly imbalanced dataset).

4.A) Define Churn ¶

Once you've done some preliminary analysis, create a column Churn to use as the label for your model. I suggest using the Cancellation Confirmation events to define your churn, which happen for both paid and free users. As a bonus task, you can also look into the Downgrade events.

4.A.a) Cancellation Confirmation Events ¶

Deriving churn (by adding a new column) from the Cancellation Confirmation Events in page column.

In [20]:
# Function to check if user has confirmed cancellation (churn) - identifying churn event
detect_churn = udf(lambda x: 1 if x == "Cancellation Confirmation" else 0, IntegerType())
df = df.withColumn("churn", detect_churn("page"))

# Applying Churn flag to the entire window (dataset) for each user - identifying users who have churned
windowval = Window.partitionBy("userId")
df = df.withColumn("churn", sum("churn").over(windowval))
In [21]:
# Sanity check - number of users who churned

# Interactions by churn type (percentage)
data = df.groupby("churn","page").count().alias("count").toPandas()

# Churned users
data_churned = data[data['churn']==1]
data_churned['count']=data_churned['count']/data_churned['count'].sum()

# Users who didn't churn
data_notchurned = data[data['churn']==0]
data_notchurned['count']=data_notchurned['count']/data_notchurned['count'].sum()

# Data append
data = data_churned.append(data_notchurned, sort=False)

5. Feature Engineering ¶

Once you've familiarized yourself with the data, build out the features you find promising to train your model on. To work with the full dataset, you can follow the following steps.

  • Write a script to extract the necessary features from the smaller subset of data
  • Ensure that your script is scalable, using the best practices discussed in Lesson 3
  • Try your script on the full data set, debugging your script if necessary

If you are working in the classroom workspace, you can just extract features based on the small subset of data contained here. Be sure to transfer over this work to the larger dataset when you work on your Spark cluster.

Putting it all together¶

In [78]:
def feature_engineering(df):
    '''
    Extracting features from the original dataframe.
    These features will then be used by the ML algorithm to predict churn.
    
    
    Inputs
        dataframe (pyspark dataframe) - original dataset (whith churn already defined - new column 'churn')
        
    Outputs
        data - new dataframe with all the features extracted/computed from the original dataset
    '''
    
    print("-> Starting Feature Engineering...")
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    
    # Number of songs
    print("* Number of songs")
    feature_nsongs = df.filter(df['song']!='null').select('userID','song').groupBy('userID').count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'totalsongs').sort(col("count").desc())
     
    # Number of Thumbs Up
    print("* Number of Thumbs Up")
    feature_thumbsup = df.filter(df['page']=='Thumbs Up').select('userID','page').groupBy('userID').count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'totalthumbsup').sort(col("count").desc())
     
    # Number of Thumbs Down
    print("* Number of Thumbs Down")
    feature_thumbsdown = df.filter(df['page']=='Thumbs Down').select('userID','page').groupBy('userID').count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'totalthumbsdown').sort(col("count").desc())
       
    # Number of friends added
    print("* Number of friends added")
    feature_addfriend = df.filter(df['page']=='Add Friend').select('userID','page').groupBy('userID').count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'friendsadded').sort(col("count").desc())

    # Number of songs added to playlist
    print("* Number of songs added to playlist")
    feature_addplist = df.filter(df['page']=='Add to Playlist').select('userID','page').groupBy('userID').count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'songsadded').sort(col("count").desc())
    
    # Number of downgrades
    print("* Number of downgrades")
    feature_downgrade = df.filter(df['page']=='Submit Downgrade').select('userID','page').groupBy('userID').count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'downgrades').sort(col("count").desc())
    
    # Average number of songs per session
    print("* Number of songs per session")
    feature_songssession = df.filter(df.page=="NextSong").groupby("userId", "sessionId").count()
    feature_songssession = feature_songssession.groupby("userId").agg(avg(feature_songssession["count"]).alias("avgSongPerSession")).sort("userId")
    
    # Number of distinct artist the user has listened to
    print("* Number of distinct artist the user has listened to")
    feature_artists = df.select("userId", "artist").dropDuplicates().groupby("userId").count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'artists').sort(col("count").desc())
    
    # Number of sessions
    print("* Number of sessions")
    feature_sessions = df.select("userId", "sessionId").dropDuplicates().groupby("userId").count().withColumnRenamed('count', 'sessions').sort(col("count").desc())
    
    # Average session duration
    print("* Average session duration")
    session_maxtime = df.groupBy('userId', 'sessionId').max('ts').withColumnRenamed('max(ts)', 'end')
    session_mintime = df.groupBy('userId', 'sessionId').min('ts').withColumnRenamed('min(ts)', 'start')
    session_duration = session_mintime.join(session_maxtime,['userId', 'sessionId'])
    session_duration = session_duration.select('userId', 'sessionId', ((session_duration.end-session_duration.start)/(1000*60)).alias('session_duration_min'))
    # computing average
    feature_avg_session_user = session_duration.groupBy('userId').agg(avg('session_duration_min').alias('avg_session_duration')).sort(col("avg_session_duration").desc())
    feature_avg_session_user = feature_avg_session_user.na.fill(0)
    
    # User lifetime
    print("* User lifetime")
    max_time_user = df.groupby("userId").max("ts").sort("userId")
    reg_time_user = df.select("userId", "registration").dropDuplicates().sort("userId")
    feature_user_lifetime = reg_time_user.join(max_time_user, reg_time_user.userId == max_time_user.userId).select(reg_time_user["userId"], ((max_time_user["max(ts)"]-reg_time_user["registration"])/(1000*60)).alias("lifetime_minutes")).sort(col("lifetime_minutes").desc())
    
    # Categorical Feature - Gender
    print("* Categorical Feature - Gender")
    feature_gender = df.select("userId", "gender").dropDuplicates().replace(["F", "M"], ["0", "1"], "Gender").select('userId', col('gender').cast('int'))
    
    # Categorical Feature - Account type (level)
    print("* Categorical Feature - Account type (level)")
    max_time_user = df.groupby("userId").max("ts").withColumnRenamed('max(ts)', 'ts').sort("userId")
    most_recent_level = df.select("userId", "level","ts").dropDuplicates().sort("userId")
    cond = [most_recent_level.userId == max_time_user.userId, most_recent_level.ts == max_time_user.ts]
    feature_level = most_recent_level.join(max_time_user, cond).select(max_time_user.userId,most_recent_level.level)
    feature_level = feature_level.select("userId","level")
    feature_level = feature_level.replace(["free", "paid"], ["0", "1"], "level")

    # Categorical Feature - Churn
    print("* Categorical Feature - Churn (target feature)")
    feature_target = df.select('userId', col('churn').alias('target_churn')).dropDuplicates()
    
    # Joining all features
    data = feature_gender.join(feature_nsongs,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_thumbsdown,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_addfriend,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_addplist,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_downgrade,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_songssession,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_artists,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_sessions,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_avg_session_user,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_user_lifetime,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_thumbsup,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_level,'userID','outer') \
    .join(feature_target,'userID','outer') \
    .drop('userID') \
    .fillna(0)

    
    print ("-> Final dataframe with:",data.count(), "rows and ",len(data.dtypes),"columns")
    print ("-> Duration:",datetime.datetime.now()-start,"s")
    print ("-> Process finished")
    
    return data

6.C) Training (with hyperparameter tuning) and Predicting ¶

Models were selected from the pyspark documentation: https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/ml-classification-regression.html During training, all the hyperparameters are tunned using GridSearch for that

In [22]:
def train_predict(train, test):
    '''
    This function will train several models on the train and test datasets previously built.
    All the models will be evaluated regarding accuracy, f-1 score and time it took to train, all the results will then be plotted.    
    
    Inputs
        train - train dataset
        test - test dataset
        
    Outputs
        classifier - all the classifiers that were tested
        accuracy - accuracy score for all the classifiers
        f1score - f1 score for all the classifiers
        timetrain - the time it took for training for each one of the classifiers
        bestclass - best classifier based on f1 score
    '''
    
    # Auxiliar lists
    classifier = []
    accuracy = []
    f1score = []
    timetrain = []
    f1score_aux = 0
    f1score_aux2 = 0
    
    ### Training and predicting
    
    ## Random Forest Classifier
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    model = RandomForestClassifier(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features")
    paramGrid = ParamGridBuilder().addGrid(model.maxDepth,[5, 10]).addGrid(model.impurity,['entropy', 'gini']).addGrid(model.numTrees ,[10, 20]).build()
    f1_eval = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName='f1')
    crossval = CrossValidator(estimator=model,estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid,evaluator=f1_eval,numFolds=3)
    
    rfmodel = crossval.fit(train)
    results = rfmodel.transform(test)
    evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(predictionCol="prediction")
    
    # Saving results
    classifier.append("Random Forest Classifier")
    accuracy.append(evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "accuracy"}))
    f1score_aux = (evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "f1"}))
    f1score.append(f1score_aux)
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    timetrain.append((end-start).total_seconds())
    bestclass = rfmodel

    
    ## Gradient Boosted Trees
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    model = GBTClassifier(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features",maxIter=10,seed=42)
    paramGrid = ParamGridBuilder().addGrid(model.maxDepth,[2, 3, 5]).addGrid(model.maxIter ,[5, 10]).build()
    f1_eval = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName='f1')
    crossval = CrossValidator(estimator=model,estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid,evaluator=f1_eval,numFolds=3)
    
    gbtmodel = crossval.fit(train)
    results = gbtmodel.transform(test)
    evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(predictionCol="prediction")
    
    # Saving results
    classifier.append("Gradient Boosted Trees")
    accuracy.append(evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "accuracy"}))
    f1score_aux2 = (evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "f1"}))
    f1score.append(f1score_aux2)
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    timetrain.append((end-start).total_seconds())
    if f1score_aux2>f1score_aux:
        bestclass=gbtmodel
        f1score_aux=f1score_aux2
     
    
    ## Decision Tree Classifier
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    model = DecisionTreeClassifier(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features",seed=42)
    paramGrid = ParamGridBuilder().addGrid(model.impurity,['entropy', 'gini']).addGrid(model.maxDepth,[2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 10, 15]).build()
    f1_eval = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName='f1')
    crossval = CrossValidator(estimator=model,estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid,evaluator=f1_eval,numFolds=3)
    
    dtmodel = crossval.fit(train)
    results = dtmodel.transform(test)
    evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(predictionCol="prediction")
    
    # Saving results
    classifier.append("Decision Tree Classifier")
    accuracy.append(evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "accuracy"}))
    f1score_aux2 = (evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "f1"}))
    f1score.append(f1score_aux2)
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    timetrain.append((end-start).total_seconds())
    if f1score_aux2>f1score_aux:
        bestclass=dtmodel
        f1score_aux=f1score_aux2
    
    
    ## Logistic Regression
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    
    model = LogisticRegression(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features",maxIter=10)
    paramGrid = ParamGridBuilder().addGrid(model.elasticNetParam,[0.0, 0.1, 0.4, 1.0]).addGrid(model.regParam,[0.0, 0.05, 0.1]).build()
    f1_eval = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName='f1')
    crossval = CrossValidator(estimator=model,estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid,evaluator=f1_eval,numFolds=3)
    
    lrmodel = crossval.fit(train)
    results = lrmodel.transform(test)
    evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(predictionCol="prediction")
    
    # Saving results
    classifier.append("Logistic Regression")
    accuracy.append(evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "accuracy"}))
    f1score_aux2 = (evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "f1"}))
    f1score.append(f1score_aux2)
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    timetrain.append((end-start).total_seconds())
    if f1score_aux2>f1score_aux:
        bestclass=lrmodel
        f1score_aux=f1score_aux2
    
    
    ## LinearSVC
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    
    model = LinearSVC(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features")
    paramGrid = ParamGridBuilder().addGrid(model.maxIter ,[5, 10]).addGrid(model.regParam ,[0.01, 0.05, 0.1]).build()
    f1_eval = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName='f1')
    crossval = CrossValidator(estimator=model,estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid,evaluator=f1_eval,numFolds=3)
    
    lsvcmodel = crossval.fit(train)
    results = lsvcmodel.transform(test)
    evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(predictionCol="prediction")
    
    # Saving results
    classifier.append("Linear SVC")
    accuracy.append(evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "accuracy"}))
    f1score_aux2 = (evaluator.evaluate(results, {evaluator.metricName: "f1"}))
    f1score.append(f1score_aux2)
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    timetrain.append((end-start).total_seconds())
    if f1score_aux2>f1score_aux:
        bestclass=lsvcmodel
        f1score_aux=f1score_aux2
   
    return classifier, accuracy, f1score, timetrain, bestclass;

def print_scores(classifier, accuracy, f1score, timetrain):
    
    '''
    This function will plot the scores attained for each one of the classifiers.
    
    Inputs
        classifier - all the classifiers that were tested
        accuracy - accuracy score for all the classifiers
        f1score - f1 score for all the classifiers
        timetrain - the time it took for training for each one of the classifiers
        
    Outputs
        NA
    '''
    
    # Creating dataframe with metrics
    metrics = pd.DataFrame(columns=['classifier', 'accuracy', 'f1score','time'])
    metrics['classifier']=classifier
    metrics['accuracy']=accuracy
    metrics['f1score']=f1score
    metrics['time']=timetrain
    
    print(metrics)
    
    # Accuracy
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
    sns.set(style="darkgrid")
    ax = sns.barplot(x='classifier', y='accuracy', orient="v", data=metrics)
    ax.set_title("Accuracy by classifier")
    ax.set_xlabel("Classifier")
    ax.set_ylabel("Accuracy")
    ax.set_ylim(0, 1)
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.4f'), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
    
    # F1score
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
    sns.set(style="darkgrid")
    ax = sns.barplot(x='classifier', y='f1score', orient="v", data=metrics)
    ax.set_title("f1score by classifier")
    ax.set_xlabel("Classifier")
    ax.set_ylabel("f1score")
    ax.set_ylim(0, 1)
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.4f'), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
    
    
    # Time to train
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
    sns.set(style="darkgrid")
    ax = sns.barplot(x='classifier', y='time', orient="v", data=metrics)
    ax.set_title("Time to train by classifier")
    ax.set_xlabel("Classifier")
    ax.set_ylabel("Time to train [s]")
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.4f'), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
    
    
    return;

7. Conclusion ¶

The end-to-end project was successfuly implemented in this workspace. All the data loading, processing, feature engineering and machine learning was done using Spark (PySpark).

For the churn prediction model, 13 new features were built (derived from the original dataset). Moreover, 5 classification models were trained on the training set (with crossvalidation) and the hyperparameters were tuned using Grid Search. The results attained were:

Classifier Accuracy f1score Time
Random Forest Classifier 0.777778 0.747710 50.091728
Gradient Boosted Trees 0.740741 0.690657 95.441571
Decision Tree Classifier 0.722222 0.702811 56.105295
Logistic Regression 0.759259 0.720124 63.920029
Linear SVC 0.722222 0.605735 47.068066

The best classifier seems to be Random Forest, which achieved ~78% accuracy and 0,75 f1 Score.

When looking at the feature importance, the lifetime stands out meaning it has a really important role in whether the user is prone to churn or not. The second most relevant feature is Thumbs down which might be easier to understand since higher number of thumbs down might indicate the user is not satisfied with the songs that are being suggested by the application. It seems that number of friends added, average songs per session and average session duration also have an important role in churn prediction.

Challenges¶

There were two main challenges during this project. The first one is related with the implementation in Spark (PySpark). Although it is pretty intuitive and straightforward, there was the need to study the official documentation and to explore all the features available.

The second one, and most challenging, is the brainstorming needed for the feature engineering process. This is much more than just data transformation, we need to understand what QoE means and how it might be characterized in order to derive meaninful features. It requires a lot of exploratory analysis for that purpose.

Improvement & next steps¶

Although we achieved a great result (78% acc and 0,75 f1 score), there are some aspects that could be improved:

  • Work with the complete dataset in order to have more samples and, ideally, have a balanced data set (similar number of churn and not churn samples/users);
  • Improve feature engineering by adding more features such as OS or User Location , and by deriving new ones from the existing data. We could also add knowledge/information from other datasources that could help us profiling our customers in a more meaningful way.
